---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = "Vampire Crawlers Beginner's Guide — Tips, Basics & Getting Started (2026)";
const description = "New to Vampire Crawlers? This beginner's guide covers card types, combat basics, deckbuilding tips, dungeon progression, and how to survive your first runs.";
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonical="https://vampcrawlers.cc/guides/beginners-guide">
  <article>
    <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-extrabold text-white mb-1">Beginner's Guide</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-500 mb-6">Everything new players need to know about poncle's turn-based deckbuilder.</p>

    <div class="toc">
      <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
      <ol>
        <li><a href="#what-is">What Is Vampire Crawlers?</a></li>
        <li><a href="#cards">Understanding Cards & Colors</a></li>
        <li><a href="#combat">Combat Basics</a></li>
        <li><a href="#village">The Village Hub</a></li>
        <li><a href="#early">Early Game Strategy</a></li>
        <li><a href="#tips">Quick Tips</a></li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <h2 id="what-is">What Is Vampire Crawlers?</h2>
    <p>Vampire Crawlers is a <strong>turn-based deckbuilder with roguelite elements</strong> from poncle, the creators of Vampire Survivors. Released April 21, 2026 on Steam, Xbox Series S|X, PS5, and Nintendo Switch. Unlike Vampire Survivors (which is real-time bullet heaven), Crawlers is a <strong>turn-based card game</strong> where you build decks, explore dungeons, and chain card combos.</p>
    <div class="info-box"><strong>Key Difference:</strong> Vampire Survivors is real-time auto-attack. Vampire Crawlers is turn-based — you play cards one at a time. Strategy > reflexes.</div>

    <h2 id="cards">Understanding Cards & Colors</h2>
    <p>Cards are color-coded by type:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong class="text-red-400">Red = Attack</strong> — Deal damage to enemies. Your primary tool.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-blue-400">Blue = Defense</strong> — Generate Armor to protect your Crawlers.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-yellow-400">Yellow = Stat Boost</strong> — Temporarily boost stats. Some are Destroy-type (one use).</li>
      <li><strong class="text-purple-400">Purple = Mana</strong> — Generate Mana to play more cards.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-teal-400">Teal = Character</strong> — Each character adds unique effects to your deck.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="combat">Combat Basics</h2>
    <p>Combat is turn-based. You play cards using <strong>Mana</strong>. Key concepts:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Mana</strong> — Resource for playing cards. Generated by purple Mana cards.</li>
      <li><strong>Armor</strong> — Absorbs damage. Generated by blue Defense cards.</li>
      <li><strong>Combos</strong> — Playing cards in ascending mana cost order increases your combo multiplier for bonus damage.</li>
      <li><strong>Evolutions</strong> — Certain cards can evolve into stronger versions when paired with specific items.</li>
      <li><strong>Encounters</strong> — Each dungeon floor has enemy encounters. Beat all enemies to advance.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Combo Stack:</strong> The Combo Stack relic (from the Tutorial) gives you a damage multiplier for playing cards in ascending mana cost order. Prioritize low-cost cards early in each encounter, then ramp up to high-cost finishers.</div>

    <h2 id="village">The Village Hub</h2>
    <p>Between dungeon runs, you return to the Village. Key locations:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Gorton Bell Inn</strong> — Buy and equip characters (up to 5).</li>
      <li><strong>Blacksmith</strong> — Add gem slots to cards (unlocked by Stardust Anvil relic).</li>
      <li><strong>Fortune Teller</strong> — Arcana system (unlocked by Polentir relic).</li>
      <li><strong>Museum</strong> — View and toggle collected relics.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="early">Early Game Strategy</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Start with Mad Forest.</strong> It's the only starting dungeon and teaches basic mechanics.</li>
      <li><strong>Reach Level 10 in Mad Forest ASAP.</strong> Unlocks Inlaid Library, even if you die after.</li>
      <li><strong>Collect the Combo Stack relic first.</strong> It's in the tutorial and essential for damage scaling.</li>
      <li><strong>Buy characters at the Inn.</strong> More characters = more cards in your starter deck = more options.</li>
      <li><strong>Don't bloat your deck.</strong> A lean deck with synergistic cards beats a bloated one.</li>
      <li><strong>Prioritize Mana cards early.</strong> You need mana to play your best cards. Empty Tome (0 cost) is great.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2 id="tips">Quick Tips</h2>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Level thresholds unlock dungeons!</strong> You don't need to complete the dungeon — just hit the level (10/15). Die immediately after, the unlock still counts.</div>
    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Don't skip relics.</strong> Relics are permanent upgrades that carry across all runs. They're hidden in breakable objects in specific dungeons. Prioritize collecting them.</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Gems (unlocked by Gem Hammer) add permanent bonuses to individual cards</li>
      <li>Arcanas (unlocked by Polentir) provide run-wide passive bonuses</li>
      <li>After buying 5 characters, Disco Mode has a 10% chance to trigger — giving you a 5% discount</li>
    </ul>

